You already can use the same spring batch database tables from multiple applications so long as the job names are unique.  Each application would contain it&#39;s own list of @Job beans that you create and that the application can manage (launch, stop, restart etc) while sharing the same spring batch database tables as other applications.  

Spring batch provides a JobRegistry (https://docs.spring.io/spring-batch/docs/current/api/org/springframework/batch/core/configuration/JobRegistry.html) that can be used to see which jobs exist in each application.  It can be populated with your @Job beans on startup 
  

    @Configuration
    public class SpringBatchConfiguration {
    
         
        @Autowired
        private JobRegistry jobRegistry;
    
        // populate the jobRegistry with all @Job beans at startup   
        @Bean
        public JobRegistryBeanPostProcessor jobRegistryBeanPostProcessor() {
            JobRegistryBeanPostProcessor postProcessor = new JobRegistryBeanPostProcessor();
            postProcessor.setJobRegistry(jobRegistry);
            return postProcessor;
        }
    
        
    }

